    <body><div type="letter">
      <p>Ockham 13th March Tuesdy. 5 o'clock</p>
      <p>Dearest Mate. I am very much better today, &amp; quite coming round again. I think you will like to see Locock's letter to me. From it as well as from something he said in London, He seems rather to think it would be a good thing for me soon to increase the family. He has I believe no doubt that it would operate</p>
      <p>as an immediate cure, &amp; from his experience of my constitution &amp; weak points, hopes he might prevent all ill consequences afterwards, by a totally different system, though I do not think he is sanguine as to my nursing again.--</p>
      <p>I am inclined to think London likely to be very pernicious to me, were I to go in a fortnight as proposed, to remain some weeks.-- I will tell you in my next letter how I propose to obviate the evils of it, &amp; yet to be there sufficiently</p>
      <p>to answer some ends that I think with you are desirable.-- First though, I will now say on the subject, that I intend to give out, to Lady Philips &amp; others, that I shall not be in Town this year,-- and will you do the same?-- Do not think, sweetest mate, that the wayward bird has got into a fuss, or set herself against anything that is reasonable. I assure ou it is not so, but I feel my weakness must not be trifled with.-- I shall tell ou my plans more fully</p>
      <p>tomorrow.--</p>
      <p>I had ou long letter from Exeter, this morning. Why do you not put X post, as I do?-- I like your account of the lady, &amp; the residence, &amp; hope she will do him Mr F good.--</p>
      <p>There has been such rain last night &amp; this morning as must I think have made a fine flood, but though I went out today in the britska, I was not in the flowing quarters, so have seen nothing.--</p>
      <p>About the leather sofa cover. Minter writes me</p>
      <p>that it is not yielding enough for a sofa of that description, &amp; must be given up in consequence, which I regret as I find it is much less expensive than I had any idea of, &amp; for appearance would be far preferable to anything else.-- So I have re-ordered the canvas, &amp; must presently consider about a nice cover for it.--</p>
      <p>I now recollect your telling me about the Alhambra carpet, &amp; your having ordered no border, which I believe I at the time</p>
      <p>agreed to.-- Hester tells me however that it will be very unfinished without unless it goes close round. I have on my own responsibility therefore, ordered one. It is to be very narrow, &amp; something of a pattern, merely just to give a finish.-- As I am anxious, with my plans about London, to leave everything in the arrangements, very unfinished, I think I shall scarcely write to you about some of those I am anxious for ultimately, one of which</p>
      <p>is a carpet in the back drawing room. I find the present Turkey carpet so unsuitable in every way, that we must clearly have one on purpose. A Turkey carpet is not only totally incongruous with the style of the room &amp; furniture, but this one fits so badly that in order to be able to open the doors it is necessary to turn up a great piece, which of course spoils the whole effect &amp; is very clumsy.-- I think this however for the</p>
      <p>present season, will be rather an advantage.--</p>
      <p>I believe I must also have a carpet for our bed-room, as I find we have none that will at all do.--</p>
      <p>I am sure you will approve the avis's views as soon as she comes fully to explain them &amp; ou will probably be glad that she makes up her mind as to what she likes, as ou has sometimes grumbled a little at her referring everything to you.--</p>
      <p>I am glad you do not mean to part with , as it is so improvable.--</p>
      <p>Pray return me Locock's letter. You will not understand the "sources of enjoyment," in the first page. It is in reply to something I had said; as also where he says it is not fair of me to expect too much from him in your absence.--</p>
      <p>There is yet no symptom of the monthly return.-- It is one day past the time.--</p>
    </div></body>
